[How can I get word-level timestamps in OpenAI&#39;s Whisper ASR?](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/73822353/how-can-i-get-word-level-timestamps-in-openais-whisper-asr)<br/>2. [Search code, repositories, users, issues, pull requests...](https://github.com/openai/whisper/discussions/3)<br/><br/># OpenAI Whisper: Transcribing with Timestamps and Segments<br/><br/>## Getting Word-Level Timestamps<br/><br/>In OpenAI Whisper version 20231117 and later, you can extract word-level timestamps by setting `word_timestamps=True` in the `transcribe()` function:[1]<br/><br/>```python<br/>import whisper<br/><br/>model = whisper.load_model("large")<br/>transcript = model.transcribe(<br/>    audio="toto.mp3",<br/>    word_timestamps=True<br/>)<br/><br/>for segment in transcript['segments']:<br/>    print(''.join(f"\{word['word']\}[\{word['start']\}/\{word['end']\}]" <br/>                  for word in segment['words']))<br/>```<br/><br/>This returns output like: `Toto,[2.98/3.4] I[3.4/3.82] have[3.82/3.96]...`[1]<br/><br/>## How It Works<br/><br/>Word-level timestamps are generated using cross-attention patterns and dynamic time warping (DTW).[2][4] The `transcribe()` function includes parameters like `prepend_punctuations` and `append_punctuations` to control how punctuation is merged with words when `word_timestamps=True`.[2]<br/><br/>## Important Limitations<br/><br/>Whisper is not explicitly trained for word-level timestamps—the feature is produced by an inference-time trick that uses cross-attention weights.[3] This means the output is not perfectly accurate, especially when dealing with pauses between words.[3]<br/><br/>## Alternative Solutions<br/><br/>For more accurate word-level timing, you can use third-party libraries:[1]<br/>- **whisper-timestamped**: Built on cross-attention weights with improved accuracy<br/>- **stable-ts**: MIT-licensed tool that accesses timestamp token predictions |

**Script: `transcribe_meeting.py`**
- Uses **moviepy** to open the video and export audio to a temporary WAV.
- Uses **openai-whisper** (model `base`) to transcribe that audio.
- Writes a timestamped transcript to **`meeting_transcript.txt`** in the project directory.

**Run**
- The script ran successfully on the ~31-minute video (audio extraction, then Whisper transcription).
- Output file: **`/Users/myhomefolder/my-development/compression/meeting_transcript.txt`**.

**Transcript format**
- Header with source path and “Generated by transcribe_meeting.py”.
- One segment per block, with time range and text, e.g.:
  - `[00:00:00.000 - 00:00:02.760] later on and we can share the recording with others.`
  - `[00:00:02.760 - 00:00:03.840] That's awesome.`
- Segments continue for the full meeting (e.g. OSDR, payload records, physical science, Aaron Persaud, user groups, etc.).

**Dependencies**
- `requirements-transcribe.txt` lists `moviepy>=1.0.3` and `openai-whisper>=20231117`.
- A project **`.venv`** was created and used; run again with:

- For better accuracy (at the cost of speed and RAM), change `WHISPER_MODEL` in the script from `"base"` to `"small"` or `"medium"`.

import re
path_in = "meeting_transcript_improved.txt"
path_out = "meeting_transcript_final.txt"
text = open(path_in, encoding="utf-8").read()

# 1) Explicit replacements (order matters for overlapping cases)
text = text.replace("TechCorp", "TechPort")
text = text.replace("celldrop", "cell-drop")
text = text.replace("Celldrop", "cell-drop")

# 2) "tech port" -> TechPort (lowercase form)
text = re.sub(r"\btech port\b", "TechPort", text, flags=re.IGNORECASE)

# 3) Capitalize acronyms (whole-word)
acronyms = [
    (r"\bosdr\b", "OSDR"), (r"\bpsi\b", "PSI"), (r"\bbps\b", "BPS"),
    (r"\baug\b", "AWG"), (r"\bksc\b", "KSC"), (r"\bapi\b", "API"),
    (r"\btrl\b", "TRL"), (r"\biss\b", "ISS"), (r"\bcad\b", "CAD"),

]
